<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10048a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10048a">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10048a"> 48(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Berta fila a cavallo / m Charlemagne</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La reine Berthe n&apos;est nullement un personnage l&eacute;gendaire, comme on pourrait le supposer. <mark>Berthe</mark> aux Grands Pieds, femme de P&eacute;pin le Bref, <mark>m&egrave;re de Charlemagne</mark>, vivait au viiie si&egrave;cle. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> La reine Berthe voulait donner toujours le bon exemple &agrave; ses sujets; elle ne perdait pas une minute de son temps, et m&ecirc;me pendant les heures consacr&eacute;es <mark>&agrave; sa promenade &agrave; cheval, elle filait</mark> &agrave; la vitesse de celui-ci le lin de sa quenouille. <font color="green">[Queen Bertha was not at all a fictitious character, as one might assume. Bertha of the Big Feet, the wife of Pepin the Short, mother of Charlemagne, lived in the 8th century. Queen Bertha always wanted to set a good example for her subjects and never wasted a minute of her time, and even in the time allotted to her horseback riding she span the linen of her distaff at the horse&apos;s pace.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 83</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
